# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: university-of-salerno
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] AUR has its origins soon after World War II.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] David Colin, an American journalist in Italy prior to and during the war, settled in Rome.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] While American students and professors visited Rome, Colin helped foster cultural exchanges between Americans and their Italian counterparts.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] Over time, informal discussions at his home became more formalized, turning into structured lectures and classes.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] His wife, Joan Carpenter, assisted Colin with this undertaking.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] George Tesoro, an Italian who left Italy in 1940 in protest against Mussolini's fascist regime, began to collaborate with Colin.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] As the program grew, The American University in Rome became reality when AUR was incorporated in 1969 in the District of Columbia with its academic headquarters located in Rome, Italy.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] Upon incorporation, Tesoro served as chairman until 1983, when Joseph D.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] Ventura, then vice chair, succeeded him.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] During Ventura's time as chairman, the board of trustees became a degree-granting institution from the District of Columbia in 1986.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] Margaret Giannini, a professional in the scientific and medical research field, became board chair and served until 2003.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] Under her 16 years of leadership, the university grew in its student and faculty numbers, curriculum offerings, and financial and management systems.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] Giannini initiated AUR's first accreditation with the Accrediting Council of Independent Colleges and Schools in 1992 and planted the seeds for Middle States accreditation.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] After operating from different locations in central Rome for almost 25 years, AUR moved to its current campus in 1993.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] The campus is located on top of the Janiculum, Rome's highest hill, offering views of the city.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] Most of its buildings are located on Via Pietro Roselli adjacent to a portion of the Aurelian Wall.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] The campus was extended in early 2018 to include an Art Studio, exhibition space and classrooms on via Angelo Masina.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] This building is adjacent to, and shares garden space with, the American Academy in Rome.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] The main campus includes two gardens centered around the main A and B buildings, the Evans Hall Library, and the Auriana Auditorium.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] The main teaching block (Building B) is part of a Barnabite monastery.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] In 2025, the university announced a major expansion and renewal of its campus.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] The American University of Rome is governed a board of trustees, president, and a senate.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] The highest governing body, the board of trustees, is responsible for overseeing the university and maintaining its academic and financial health and welfare.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] Among other duties, the board appoints the president and has final approval of changes to the curriculum proposed by the AUR Senate (the body which, forms and amends academic policies and includes a student government representative).
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] The current president of the university is Dr.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] Scott Sprenger who assumed the position in July 2020, taking over from Dr.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] Richard Hodges OBE, who was named President Emeritus & Professor Emeritus upon completing his tenure.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] AUR is a member of the Association of American International Colleges and Universities and The American International Consortium of Academic Libraries (AMICAL).
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] The American University of Rome is a liberal arts university with a student-faculty ratio of roughly 16:1.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] AUR's undergraduate student body of roughly 500 students is multicultural and representative of over 30 nationalities.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] The American University of Rome is regionally accredited by the Middle States Commission on Higher Education, which is an institutional accrediting agency recognized by the U.S.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] Secretary of Education and the Council for Higher Education Accreditation.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] The American University of Rome is licensed by the Department of Education of the State of Delaware to award associate, bachelor's and master's degrees.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] In Italy, AUR is registered as a legal entity with the Rome Tribunal and it is authorized to operate in Italy by the Ministry of Education, Universities and Research.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] AUR offers three master's degrees (in Peace Studies, Sustainable Cultural Heritage and Food Studies) and eleven bachelor's degree programs with 16 concentrations or tracks, two associate degree programs, and eighteen minors.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] Students live off-campus mostly near the university, giving the opportunity to allow the students to immerse in the surrounding communities.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] The AUR community of students and faculty publishes a literary journal of student works called Remus each year.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] AUR student run organisations include Student Government and a variety of clubs such as: Veterans Club, Business Club, Communication Club, Culture Club, Italian Studies Club, and International Relations Club which also organises AUR's Harvard National Model United Nations delegation.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] The Communication club also supports AUR's Communication Week which is a showcase of the American University of Rome students communications and English work.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] The Wolves and She-Wolves are the American University of Rome's soccer clubs which play competitively against Rome's other universities including La Sapienza and Roma Tre University.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] Both AUR's men's and women's teams were founding members of their respective intercollegiate tournaments; the men's "Campionato di Calcio delle Università Romane" (2005) and the women's "Campionato Calcio Feminile delle Università Romane" in 2006.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] AUR Wolves, men's soccer team, won the Universities of Rome a5 Football Championship on April 26, 2018, their first trophy since co-founding the league in 2005.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] The first mascot in Roman university athletics, Wolfie has been representing AUR since 2006.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] Originally named "Romulus" in reference to the mythical founder of Rome, the name Wolfie was popularized by students and later formally adopted.
[src:university-of-salerno/american-university-of-rome] The American University of Rome hosts a number of study abroad students but also promotes the opportunity for resident students to study abroad from AUR using the AURA program.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] Before the Roman conquest, the ancient ***Abellinum*** was a centre of the Samnite Hirpini, located on the Civita hill some 4 kilometres (2 mi) outside the current town, in what is now Atripalda.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] The city could correspond to the ancient *Velecha*, documented by coins found in the area.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] *Abellinum* was conquered by the Romans in 293 BC, changing name several times in the following centuries (*Veneria*, *Livia*, *Augusta*, *Alexandriana*, and *Abellinatium*).
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] However, the construction of a true Roman town occurred only after the conquest by Lucius Cornelius Sulla in the civil wars in 89 BC.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] He razed the old site and in 82 BC founded the colony Veneria Abellinatium on the left bank of the river Sabato.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] The new city was surrounded by massive walls and had an orthogonal *hippodamian* urban layout.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] In 7 AD Augustus changed its name to Livia Augusta in honour of his wife, Livia Drusilla who owned the territories between Abellinum and Aeclanum.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] In the 3rd century Alexander Severus expanded the colony under the title of Livia Augusta Alexandrina with a massive immigration of oriental settlers.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] This helped to spread ancient Levantine cults such as Sol Invictus in the territory.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] There followed economic crises (III and IV centuries), violent earthquakes (346) and disastrous volcanic eruptions (472).
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] The town was Christianised around 500, becoming an episcopal seat.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] There were invasions of the Goths (535–555) and the Vandals.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] After the Lombard conquest of southern Italy, the ancient city was abandoned in 568 (it is disputed if completely or partly) and a new settlement grew on the Terra hill, corresponding to the modern Avellino.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] Defended by a castle, it became part of the Duchy (later Principality) of Benevento and, after the latter's fall, of the Principality of Salerno.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] In 1100, during the Norman rule of southern Italy, it was acquired by Riccardo dell'Aquila.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] Later, King Charles I of Anjou assigned it to the Montfort family, who were succeeded by the Del Balzo and the Filangieri.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] The feudal rights to Avellino were purchased in 1581 by Don Marino I Caracciolo, duke of Atripalda, of a patrician family of Naples, who was made Prince of Avellino in 1589.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] Avellino became the main seat of the Caracciolo.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] Don Marino's son and grandson were consecutively Grand Chancellor of the Kingdom of Naples and chevaliers of the Order of the Golden Fleece.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] The grandson, Don Marino II (1587–1630), was the patron of Giambattista Basile, author of the *Pentamerone*.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] In 1820 Avellino was seat of revolutionary riots.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] However, the Unification of Italy some fifty years later did not bring any benefit to the city, being cut off from the main railway line Naples-Benevento-Foggia, and far from the sea as well.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] In 1943 the city was bombed by Allied planes in an attempt to cut off the retreat of German panzer units over the important Bridge of Ferriera.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] Avellino has suffered from seismic activity throughout its history and was struck hard by the earthquakes of 23 November 1980 and 14 February 1981.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] Avellino has also received ashfall from numerous eruptions of Vesuvius which lies almost due west; the city sits on type locality of pumice deposited from a Plinian eruption of Vesuvius about 3800 years ago.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] The 1980 Irpinia earthquake represented a turning point for the town and for the entire province of Avellino.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] Large amounts of money flowed in for infrastructure investment, and the extra money generated innovation and economic expansion more generally.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] By 2008 a per capita annual income level of €20,180 placed Avellino well above the regional average in terms of individual prosperity.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] Agriculture was at the heart of Avellino's economy until the mid-1970s, since then many younger people have moved away from family farms, and sometimes also migrated away from the area, in pursuit of higher wages.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] Nevertheless, tobacco, viticulture and especially the production of hazelnuts remain important to the local economy and, with increased investment in recent years, employ a number of people.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] The manufacturing sector plays an important role in Avellino, with two industrial zones on the eastern and western peripheries of the main urban area, at *Pianodardine* suburb, Montefredane, Prata di Principato Ultra and Pratola Serra.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] The nearest airports are those of Salerno-Pontecagnano, 51 kilometres (32 mi) to the southwest and Napoli-Capodichino, 53 kilometres (33 mi) to the west.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] The station, located where the city limits of Avellino meet Atripalda, was once the terminus for passenger rail services to Benevento, Cancello, and Rocchetta Sant'Antonio.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] The station provided a reliable link with Benevento and Salerno.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] A few long-distance trains to Naples and Rome were also added to try to reinvigorate the local economy, but these services came to an end in 2010, following cuts that saw the closure of the railway between Avellino and Rocchetta Sant'Antonio.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] A regional decree dated 9 August 2012 forced the closure of the remaining 19 local rail services.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] However, in response to protests from rail users a small number of services were reinstated on 28 October 2012.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] Near Naples the A16 connects with the A3 Autostrada, ensuring good road access with the principal population centres across Italy.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] Also important is the so-called "Ofantina" superstrada (dual carriageway) linking with several locally important towns to the east and south, en route to Salerno.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] Public transportation in Avellino is provided by AIR Campania.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] Since 2023, the service includes trolleybuses (locally referred to, inaccurately, as the *metropolitana leggera*, or light metro), on a new trolleybus route that opened on 3 April 2023.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] A trolleybus system previously operated in Avellino from 1947 to 1973.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] The ruins of the ancient Roman **Abellinum** are situated near the modern village of Atripalda, 4 kilometres (2.5 miles) east of modern Avellino.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] They include the *forum*, faced by temples, baths, parts of the Serino aqueduct and a patrician *domus*.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] There was also an amphitheatre and a brothel.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] Avellino Cathedral, with its Romanesque crypt, stands on the site of a rich Roman villa which was built around 129 BC and abandoned after the eruption of Vesuvius, and an earthquake in 346 AD.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] The church and convent of Santa Maria delle Grazie were built in 1580.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] There are some remains of the Lombard castle in Piazza Castello (Castle Square).
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] Because the castle was built at the base of a small valley, its tactical purpose continues to puzzle modern-day historians throughout Europe.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] The Fountain of Bellerophon was executed in the 17th century by Cosimo Fanzago.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] In the HBO television series *The Sopranos*, mob boss Tony Soprano has his family roots in Avellino.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] All four of Tony's grandparents emigrated from Avellino to the United States in the early 20th century.
[src:university-of-salerno/avellino] In the episode "In Camelot", Tony's uncle Corrado "Junior" Soprano claims "The whole village of Avellino settled in this area" in which the main characters live, in Essex County, New Jersey.
[src:university-of-salerno/baronissi] The town develops from the original old area named *Casali*.
[src:university-of-salerno/baronissi] The town is situated 7 km north of Salerno and it is 35 km from Avellino.
[src:university-of-salerno/baronissi] The bordering municipalities are Castiglione del Genovesi, Cava de' Tirreni, Fisciano, Mercato San Severino, Pellezzano and Salerno.
[src:university-of-salerno/baronissi] Its 11 hamlets (*frazioni*) are Acquamela, Aiello, Antessano, Capo Saragnano, Caprecano, Casal Barone, Casal Siniscalco, Fusara, Orignano, Saragnano, Sava (the most populated one).
[src:university-of-salerno/baronissi] The municipality has two train stations (Baronissi, in town's center, and Acquamela, in the homonym village), both on the line Salerno-Mercato San Severino.
[src:university-of-salerno/baronissi] It is also served by the motorway RA 2 Salerno-Avellino, at the exits "Baronissi Sud" and "Lancusi-Baronissi Nord".
[src:university-of-salerno/bocconi-university] The university offers courses in social sciences, with programs in economics, management, finance, law, political science, data and computer science, and an increasing focus on artificial intelligence.
[src:university-of-salerno/bocconi-university] Bocconi is a founding member of CEMS – The Global Alliance in Management Education.
[src:university-of-salerno/bocconi-university] Through its graduate business school, the SDA Bocconi School of Management, the university holds triple accreditation from AACSB, EQUIS, and AMBA.
[src:university-of-salerno/bocconi-university] SDA Bocconi offers MBA, Executive MBA, DBA, executive education, professional development, and certification programs.
[src:university-of-salerno/bocconi-university] Bocconi University was established in 1902 as Italy's first university to offer a degree in economics.
[src:university-of-salerno/bocconi-university] Its founder, Ferdinando Bocconi, created the university in memory of his son Luigi, who died in the 1896 Battle of Adwa during the First Italo-Ethiopian War.
[src:university-of-salerno/bocconi-university] The university’s first building opened in Largo Notari (today Via Statuto).
[src:university-of-salerno/bocconi-university] In 1941, Bocconi moved to its current main campus in Via Sarfatti 25.
[src:university-of-salerno/bocconi-university] Over the decades, the campus has expanded with new facilities, including student residences, research centers, and the business school SDA Bocconi School of Management (established in 1971).
[src:university-of-salerno/bocconi-university] Key milestones include the introduction of new degree programs in law, political science, data science and artificial intelligence, the launch of Italy’s first MBA (1974), the creation of the CEMS alliance (1988), and the completion of the new urban campus designed by SANAA in 2019.
[src:university-of-salerno/bocconi-university] The university's first building opened in 1902 on Via Statuto, near the Pinacoteca di Brera.
[src:university-of-salerno/bocconi-university] Several other administrative and research offices are located near Parco Ravizza and Viale Isonzo.
[src:university-of-salerno/bocconi-university] Bocconi provides approximately 1,800 dormitory places for students.
[src:university-of-salerno/bocconi-university] Residences include *Bocconi*, *Javotte*, *Dubini*, *Spadolini*, *Isonzo*, *Bligny*, and *Castiglioni* (opened in 2018).
[src:university-of-salerno/bocconi-university] Research activities are carried out within departments, research centers, and laboratories.
[src:university-of-salerno/bocconi-university] The Bocconi Graduate School offers 14 Master of Science (MSc) programs taught in English, 1 specialized master in English, and 1 in *Italian*.
[src:university-of-salerno/bocconi-university] Bocconi's MSc in Finance was among the first six programs worldwide to partner with the CFA Institute and the first in continental Europe.
[src:university-of-salerno/bocconi-university] Its MSc in Management and International Management includes participation in the CEMS Master in International Management, of which Bocconi is a founding member.
[src:university-of-salerno/bocconi-university] Specialized masters include: *Marketing e Comunicazione* (MiMeC); Quantitative Finance and Risk Management (MAFINRISK).
[src:university-of-salerno/bocconi-university] Double degree programs exist with CEMS partner universities, and with many universities from all over the world such as ESSEC Business School, Fudan University, and Sciences Po, London School of Economics, HEC Paris, ESADE.
[src:university-of-salerno/bocconi-university] Established in 2006, the Bocconi School of Law consolidated the university's tradition in legal studies under the "A.
[src:university-of-salerno/bocconi-university] It offers law courses in Italian and English and a summer academy (with the University of Trento and Sant'Anna School of Advanced Studies).
[src:university-of-salerno/bocconi-university] Specialized masters include: LLM in European Business and Social Law; LLM in Global Tax and Law Governance; LLM in Law of Technology and Automated Systems.
[src:university-of-salerno/bocconi-university] The School of Law also offers a number of double degree programs and exchange programs with 290 partner institutions worldwide.
[src:university-of-salerno/bocconi-university] Founded in 1971, SDA Bocconi is the university’s graduate business school, with locations also in Rome and Mumbai, and offers MBA, Executive MBA, specialized master’s, and executive education.
[src:university-of-salerno/bocconi-university] It holds triple accreditation (AACSB, EQUIS, AMBA) and publishes *Economia & Management*, an Italian management review.
[src:university-of-salerno/bocconi-university] The school also offers specialized Master programs in areas such as corporate finance, real estate management, food and beverage, fashion, design, and sports management.
[src:university-of-salerno/bocconi-university] In 2006, Bocconi's research funding came primarily from the university itself (€1.5 million), the European Union (€1.4 million), the Italian Ministry of Education, University and Research (€300,000), and external sources (€11 million).
[src:university-of-salerno/bocconi-university] In 2011, the European Research Council awarded €5 million to five social sciences and humanities projects led by Bocconi professors.
[src:university-of-salerno/bocconi-university] Bocconi has been a major recipient of European Research Council (ERC) funding since the program’s inception, securing 71 grants across all ERC schemes, particularly in the social sciences and quantitative disciplines, with approximately 35 grants active in 2025.
[src:university-of-salerno/bocconi-university] Bocconi has departments in: Accounting; Economics; Finance; Management and Technology; Marketing; Decision Sciences; Legal Studies; Social and Political Sciences; and Computing Sciences.
[src:university-of-salerno/bocconi-university] Since 2011, Bocconi's Alumni Association has awarded *Alumnus of the Year* to graduates exemplifying the values of professionalism, entrepreneurship, integrity, responsibility, and openness.
[src:university-of-salerno/bocconi-university] It replaced the *Bocconian of the Year* (since 1988) and *Master of Masters* (since 2007).
[src:university-of-salerno/bocconi-university] Past recipients include Fabrizio Saccomanni, Emma Bonino, Vittorio Colao, Nouriel Roubini, Luca de Meo, Francesca Bellettini, and Giuseppe Sala, among others.
[src:university-of-salerno/ca-foscari-university-of-venice] Ca' Foscari expanded throughout the 1900s and became a full-fledged university in 1968.
[src:university-of-salerno/ca-foscari-university-of-venice] It currently has eight departments and almost 21,000 students, and is Venice's biggest university.
[src:university-of-salerno/ca-foscari-university-of-venice] Its teaching and research is centred around economics & business, humanities, and modern languages.
[src:university-of-salerno/ca-foscari-university-of-venice] Ca' Foscari was founded as the "Regia Scuola Superiore di Commercio" (Royal College of Commerce) by a Royal Decree dated 6 August 1868, and teaching commenced in December of the same year.
[src:university-of-salerno/ca-foscari-university-of-venice] The school was the first institute of higher education in commerce in Italy.
[src:university-of-salerno/ca-foscari-university-of-venice] It also had a diplomatic section to train and educate Diplomats and commercial consular staff for overseas service and international law.
[src:university-of-salerno/ca-foscari-university-of-venice] In addition, Ca' Foscari was also created to operate as a training college for secondary school teachers of commercial subjects.
[src:university-of-salerno/ca-foscari-university-of-venice] Foreign languages were taught from the start as well as the study of foreign cultures.
[src:university-of-salerno/ca-foscari-university-of-venice] The school was parallelled only by the Institut Supérieur de Commerce d'Anvers, founded in 1853 in Antwerp, Belgium.
[src:university-of-salerno/ca-foscari-university-of-venice] Today, Ca' Foscari is still a specialised university for the study of business economics, humanitites and languages.
[src:university-of-salerno/ca-foscari-university-of-venice] Following the establishment of a national syllabus for university teaching in 1935, the Istituto Superiore di Economia e Commercio di Venezia, as it was by then called, was authorised to award four-year *laurea* degrees.
[src:university-of-salerno/ca-foscari-university-of-venice] In 1968 it obtained university status, and the name was changed to Università degli Studi di Venezia.
[src:university-of-salerno/ca-foscari-university-of-venice] In the following year two new faculties were created, of industrial chemistry and of philosophy and letters.
[src:university-of-salerno/ca-foscari-university-of-venice] It also hosts the European Centre for Living Technology as well as a Law Center.
[src:university-of-salerno/ca-foscari-university-of-venice] The QS World University Ranking by subject has placed Ca’ Foscari of Venice among the top 100 universities in the world for modern languages, among the top 150 in the world for humanities, and among the top 200 in the world for economics and management.
[src:university-of-salerno/ca-foscari-university-of-venice] The university also ranked as the third best public university in Italy for their quality of research according to ANVUR (the National Agency for the Evaluation of University Research Systems) in 2018.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] The university is formed from a variety of institutions which include thirteen academic departments organised into two schools.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] It provides undergraduate, graduate and post-graduate education, in addition to a range of international programs in multiple fields of study.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] Research is a component of each academic division, receiving funds for its scientific investigation from national and international institutions.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] D'Annunzio University's main campus in Chieti features an eclectic mix of buildings encompassing 48.9 acres.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] A satellite campus is located in Pescara, while a distance learning centre is situated in Torrevecchia Teatina.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] It is one of the youngest national university in Italy to enter the *U.S.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] News & World Report* of the world's best universities.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] In 1955, the municipal and provincial administrations of Chieti and Pescara, neighbouring cities in the region of Abruzzo in Central Italy, met to discuss about the foundation of a consortium in order to establish a non-state-owned university in the medieval town of Chieti.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] Their proposal, pursued by engineer Filippo de Apulia, was submitted to the Ministry of Public Education of Italy on 28 November 1955.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] The creation of the University Consortium of Abruzzi was officially approved in 1960 by the Prefect of Chieti, following the participation of the Chambers of Commerce and the Board of the Banks of the town, in association with over sixty municipalities from the region.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] In 1961, the faculty of letters and philosophy was inaugurated at the National Archaeology Museum of Abruzzo by the technical organising committee, chaired by Professor Ettore Paratore.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] It preceded the inauguration ceremony of the free university courses that took place on 12 November 1961.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] The following month, commerce and economics courses were introduced with an adjoining foreign languages and literatures course, following an opening ceremony held at the Marble Hall of the Province of Pescara, in the presence of Professor Carlo Izzo.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] In January 1963, an official request for the establishment of the Free University of Abruzzi was proposed by the organising committee, prompting the institutions of Chieti, Pescara and Teramo to debate the unification of the three university consortia into a single interprovincial consortium.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] On 3 March 1965, Minister of Public Education Luigi Gui signed the decree of recognition of the Gabriele D'Annunzio Free University of Abruzzo, named after the Italian writer and poet from Pescara.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] Professor Renato Balzarini was elected as the first Rector of the university and chaired the first meeting of the board of trustees, which was originally composed of fourteen members.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] The opening ceremony of the first academic year took place in Pescara on 19 March 1966, in the presence of the Minister Luigi Gui.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] During the following years, the university saw the inauguration of the faculty of medicine and surgery in Chieti, the institution of the faculties of architecture in Pescara and political sciences in Teramo.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] In addition, the course of foreign languages and literatures was finally established, after it definitely separated from the faculty of commerce and economics.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] In December 1979, Professor Aldo Bernardini was elected Rector.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] In April 1982, D'Annunzio Free University became state-supported, following the approval of the Senate of the Republic of Italy.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] It preceded the opening of the faculties of pharmacy, veterinary medicine, and natural sciences, which were placed in three provinces of the region.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] The seal of the university was inspired by a sculpture of Pietro Cascella located in the campuses of Chieti and Pescara; it reproduces the stylised form of the head of the Roman goddess of wisdom Minerva, placed on a simple base and bearing the words "Università degli Studi G.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] D'Annunzio", upon which the acronym "Ud'A" is superimposed.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] In June 1985, Professor Uberto Crescenti was elected Rector.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] In the following years, D'Annunzio University saw increased emphasis on research, reorganization of administrative structure and construction of new facilities, leading to the establishment of the Museum of Biomedical Sciences and the opening of a research and training hospital.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] On 20 February 1988, Minister Giovanni Galloni inaugurated the Viale Pindaro campus in Pescara.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] The faculties based in Teramo separated from D'Annunzio University in 1993, establishing the University of Teramo.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] The Institute of Hospitalisation and Treatment for Scientific Purposes was launched at D'Annunzio University by Minister of Health Rosy Bindi in early 2000.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] The Continuing Education Centre was also founded as a permanent training centre in the town of Torrevecchia Teatina, while the Teacher Training School (SSIS) opened in Chieti.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] The Centre for Research in Aging, supported by the Ministry of Universities and Research, gained national relevance as the first Italian centre dedicated to research into healthy aging and age-related diseases.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] In 2002, the university opened four new faculties, with a consequent increase in student numbers that led to the creation of a second teaching centre at the Madonna delle Piane campus in Chieti.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] The following year saw the birth of the D'Annunzio University Foundation and the official opening of the Centre for Research in Aging, which took place in the presence of Minister Letizia Moratti.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] In 2004, the centre was recognized with a special advisory status by the United Nations Economic and Social Council.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] The university later funded and promoted the Leonardo da Vinci University, based in Torrevecchia Teatina, which was legally recognised in 2004.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] It forms the online campus of D'Annunzio University and delivers its services exclusively online.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] Following the approval of the Gelmini's reform in 2012, all faculties were replaced by thirteen departments organized into two schools.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] D'Annunzio University's 48.9 acres (19.8 ha) main campus is centered on Madonna delle Piane in Chieti Scalo, about 3 miles (5 km) northwest of downtown Chieti.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] Its facilities are organised within a unitary structure which includes natural elements and pre-existing buildings.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] It is the statutory seat of the university and contains the central administrative offices, including the rectorate and general directorate.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] Most of the D'Annunzio University's academic programs are located on the campus in Madonna delle Piane, which houses two schools and seven departments including the School of Advanced Studies.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] It contains the main libraries of the university as well as five research centres.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] It is the home of Rectorate Auditorium which serves as the university's main venue for music concerts, lectures, and academic ceremonies.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] Giardino dei Semplici is a botanical garden operated by the D'Annunzio University.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] It is located on the southwest corner of the campus in Madonna delle Piane and hosts a collection of over 400 medicinal plant species.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] The Nature Trail is an educational trail running across the campus area and covering 1.4 kilometres (0.87 mi).
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] Many of the university's sports facilities are located in the campus.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] D'Annunzio University provides housing for undergraduates, graduate students, and professional students at the Mediterranean Village, a residence hall located on the eastside of the main campus.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] It contains a library and conference hall as well as a medical centre.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] The residential house originally provided accommodation for athletes of the 2009 Mediterranean Games.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] The campus is served by Rete Ferroviaria Italiana at the Chieti–Madonna delle Piane railway station, which connects the university to the Rome–Sulmona–Pescara railway line.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] Viale Pindaro campus spans 6.29 acres (2.55 ha) in Porta Nuova, located immediately south of downtown Pescara.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] Situated within the urban area of the city, its academic buildings were designed according to modern architecture and through the use of environmentally friendly construction practices.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] Nature Reserve Pineta Dannunziana, Aurum Museum and Pescara's Citadel of Justice are located in its surrounding area.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] Viale Pindaro campus is the home of six departments and one school, as well as one library.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] It is also houses the university language centre and the local office of the Erasmus Student Network.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] Located at the intersection of the Citadel of Justice and Viale Pindaro, Palazzo Micara is perhaps the campus' most prominent structure.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] A residential hall is located in a neighbourhood half a mile northeast of the campus.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] D'Annunzio University provides a number of undergraduate and postgraduate detached courses in the cities of Vasto, Lanciano and Torre de' Passeri.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] Torrevecchia Teatina is the home of the Distance Learning Centre, structured in the research doctorate in e-learning, development and delivery.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] It also houses the Leonardo da Vinci University, which was created on the initiative of the D'Annunzio University Foundation.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] The university's formal head is the Rector, currently Sergio Caputi.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] The Rector is elected every four years by the board of trustees.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] The role of the Rector is to represent the university and to convene and chair the board of directors, the executive committee, and the academic senate.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] The Rector may appoint one or more Vice Rectors to which it can delegate the exercise of certain functions.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] D'Annunzio University provides undergraduate, graduate and post-graduate education, in addition to a range of international programs in multiple fields of study.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] It is divided into thirteen departments, which are primary centres where teaching and research co-exist to promote scientific activities for different educational areas.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] Two or more departments, grouped according to criteria of disciplinary affinity, work as connecting structures referred to as schools.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] It is a member of the Mediterranean Universities Union, the Netval Research Universities Network, AlmaLaurea, and the Interuniversity Consortium of Northeastern Italy for Automatic Computing.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] The D'Annunzio University Library System consists of subject and interdisciplinary libraries as well as library funding of the sites of Chieti and Pescara.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] The collection covers virtually all disciplines and includes a wide array of formats – from books and journals to manuscripts and maps.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] Increasingly collections are digital and are accessible on the Internet via the library web page or the library catalog.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] The university library system also maintains subscriptions to a number of online databases which can be accessed from any student account on or off campus.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] There are also various specialized libraries and archives.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] The Medical and Scientific Library is the main science library for D'Annunzio University.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] It is located on the campus in Chieti, which also houses the Ettore Paratore Library.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] Paratore's collections focus on Humanities, Social Sciences, and Education, and occupies three floors.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] The seat of Pescara is the home of a unified library centre with individual sections focusing on Architecture, Foreign Languages and Literatures, Economics and Management Sciences.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] It houses over 129,000 books and offers nearly 300 seats.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] D'Annunzio University offers a wide range of collections which are organised into the Museum of Biomedical Sciences.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] It is located at Palazzo Arnaldo Mussolini in the historic centre of Chieti and was established in 1994 under the presidency of Luigi Capasso.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] The institution is dedicated to the knowledge and dissemination of natural sciences and history of science, focusing on biological and medical notions arising from research in archaeology, medicine and palaeontology.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] The permanent exhibition consists of more than 19,000 records and spans an area of over 16,000 square feet (1,500 m2).
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] The most celebrated items in the museum include vertebrate fossils from the Jurassic and Cretaceous periods.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] The Museum of Biomedical Sciences is also open to the general public and provides educational programming.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] It includes an auditorium and a special library, as well as a number of scientific laboratories for activities of archaeological conservation and research in anthropology.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] It receives about 13,000 visitors every year.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] The institution is a member of the International Council of Museums.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] In its 2017 report, *Il Sole 24 Ore* ranked D'Annunzio University as the 27th-best public university in Italy.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] The SCImago Institutions Rankings listed it at number 25 among the top universities nationwide, and number 502 overall among the world best universities.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] D'Annunzio University was included in the 2018 *U.S.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] News & World Report* of the world's top 1000 universities.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] Its School of Medicine and Health Sciences was also rated one of the world's top 600 medical institutions.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] According to the 2018 ANVUR report, it has the top-ranked department of physical sciences nationwide.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] In the 2017 issue of the *CWTS Leiden Ranking*, D'Annunzio University was ranked 572nd among world universities.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] The University Ranking by Academic Performance ranked it 38th among national universities and 712nd overall among academic institutions worldwide.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] In addition, it was included among the top 500 universities of Europe by Webometrics Ranking of World Universities and is one of the 48 Italian higher education institutions to appear in the 2017 report of the Center for World University Rankings.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] D'Annunzio University has long been associated with basic and advanced scientific research.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] In addition to state funding, it receives financial support from the D'Annunzio University Foundation, an organization which exists to manage gifts and donations to the university.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] The Foundation manages the university's endowment, which helps provide support for long-term university goals and for other scientific purposes.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] The former is accredited by the United Nations Economic and Social Council.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] The institutes scientific works have been published on major academic journals, including *PNAS* and *PLOS One*.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] An operational unit of sports medicine is centred on the International Centre for Professional Training (CIAPI).
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] D'Annunzio University has also established a botanical garden known as Giardino dei Semplici, containing a collection of herbs and woody plants related to traditional medicine which are used as an additional resource for scientific research.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] D'Annunzio University has produced alumni distinguished in their respective fields.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] Many graduates have been notable in the political arena, including deputy Maurizio Acerbo and mayor Luciano D'Alfonso.
[src:university-of-salerno/d-annunzio-university-of-chieti-pescara] Other notable alumni include journalist Giampiero Catone, writer Giada Trebeschi, and painter Luciano de Liberato, among others.
[src:university-of-salerno/escp-europe] It is, along with HEC and ESSEC, a member of the *Parisiennes*, an informal term designating the three most prestigious business schools in France.
[src:university-of-salerno/escp-europe] The school was established in Paris on 1 December 1819 by two former Napoleonic soldiers, Germain Legret and Amédée Brodart.
[src:university-of-salerno/escp-europe] Germain Legret had founded two business schools in Paris in 1815 and 1818, but both closed their doors rapidly.
[src:university-of-salerno/escp-europe] ESCP offered entrepreneurship education in the 1820s.
[src:university-of-salerno/escp-europe] It was modelled on the first grande école, the École Polytechnique, founded by Lazare Carnot and Gaspard Monge, but was initially more modest, in large part because it had not been supported by the state.
[src:university-of-salerno/escp-europe] The school, with its commercial museum, had gained international exposure since the 1820s, but it was not the only business school open to international students..
[src:university-of-salerno/escp-europe] Its stature and importance ascended during the 19th century and it moved to its current Parisian location on the Avenue de la République in 1898.
[src:university-of-salerno/escp-europe] In 1828, the project to put the school under the authority of the French Ministry of Commerce and Industry failed.
[src:university-of-salerno/escp-europe] The school remained independent by the intervention of Jérôme-Adolphe Blanqui, who took it over.
[src:university-of-salerno/escp-europe] Several times during the first half of the 19th century, French political developments resulted in plans to group ESCP with elite French engineering schools such as the École Polytechnique or the École Centrale Paris, but this ultimately did not happen.
[src:university-of-salerno/escp-europe] At the time, engineering schools in France and in Europe taught future businessmen.
[src:university-of-salerno/escp-europe] From 1838, the French state began to fund scholarships meant for ESCP's students.
[src:university-of-salerno/escp-europe] In 1869, the Paris Chamber of Commerce took over the school, aiming to train future business leaders in modern methods in commerce and industry.
[src:university-of-salerno/escp-europe] In 1892, ESCP set up selective admissions processes, which continued to be retained and, today, take the form of competitive exams.
[src:university-of-salerno/escp-europe] On 5 April 1973, the concept of a multi-campus business school was created, with consecutive inaugurations of campuses taking place in the United Kingdom (London in 1974, move to Oxford in 1975) and in Germany (Düsseldorf in 1975, move to Berlin in 1985).
[src:university-of-salerno/escp-europe] In 1974 the ESCP developed courses in entrepreneurship in response to internal and external forces.
[src:university-of-salerno/escp-europe] Since then, the school has deepened its European presence to become an integrated pan-European business school.
[src:university-of-salerno/escp-europe] In 2018, ESCP became an *École consulaire*, largely financed by the public Chambers of Commerce in Paris, Berlin, and Turin.
[src:university-of-salerno/escp-europe] ESCP Business School is a *grande école*, a French institution of higher education that is separate from, but parallel and often connected to, the main framework of the French public university system.
[src:university-of-salerno/escp-europe] *Grandes écoles* are elite academic institutions that admit students through an extremely competitive process, and a significant proportion of their graduates occupy the highest levels of French society.
[src:university-of-salerno/escp-europe] Similar to Ivy League universities in the United States, Oxbridge in the UK, and the C9 League in China, graduation from a *grande école* is viewed as the ideal prerequisite credential for any top government, administrative and corporate position in the nation.
[src:university-of-salerno/escp-europe] The degrees are accredited by the *Conférence des Grandes Écoles* and awarded by the French Ministry of National Education.
[src:university-of-salerno/escp-europe] Higher education business degrees in France are organized into three levels thus facilitating international mobility: the *Licence*, or Bachelor's degrees, and the Master's and Doctoral degrees.
[src:university-of-salerno/escp-europe] The Bachelors and the Masters are organized in semesters: 6 for the Bachelors and 4 for the Masters.
[src:university-of-salerno/escp-europe] Those levels of study include various "parcours" or paths based on UE (*Unités d'enseignement* or *Modules*), each worth a defined number of European credits (ECTS).
[src:university-of-salerno/escp-europe] A student accumulates those credits, which are generally transferable between paths.
[src:university-of-salerno/escp-europe] A Bachelors is awarded once 180 ECTS have been obtained (bac + 3); a Masters is awarded once 120 additional credits have been obtained (bac +5).
[src:university-of-salerno/escp-europe] The highly coveted PGE (*Programme Grande École*) ends with the degree of Master in Management (MiM).
[src:university-of-salerno/escp-europe] ESCP students can study on campuses in France (Paris), the UK (London), Spain (Madrid), Germany (Berlin), Italy (Turin), and Poland (Warsaw).
[src:university-of-salerno/escp-europe] They can spend either 6 months or 1 year on each campus according to their study choices.
[src:university-of-salerno/escp-europe] Each campus has its own specifics and develops programs with local academic institutions.
[src:university-of-salerno/escp-europe] For instance, in Spain, ESCP provides a Master in Business Project Management co-delivered with the Technical University of Madrid and in Italy, a double-degree program is available for engineers together with the Polytechnic University of Turin.
[src:university-of-salerno/escp-europe] Since 2017, ESCP has had two campuses in Paris, one near the Place de la République (in the 11th arrondissement of Paris) and another one near the Montparnasse Tower (in the 15th arrondissement of Paris).
[src:university-of-salerno/escp-europe] Each campus is dedicated to a specific range of programs.
[src:university-of-salerno/escp-europe] The campus in the 11th arrondissement hosts all the graduate programs whereas the campus in the 15th arrondissement hosts the undergraduate education, the executive education and the school's start-up Incubator, the Blue Factory.
[src:university-of-salerno/escp-europe] This organization is unique to Paris; on every other campus, undergraduate, graduate and executive programmes are dispensed in the same campus.
[src:university-of-salerno/escp-europe] ESCP has over 100 partner *grandes* é*coles* and universities worldwide, several offering dual degrees.
[src:university-of-salerno/university-of-salerno] The **University of Salerno** (Italian: *Università degli Studi di Salerno*) (in acronym UNISA) is a university located in Fisciano and in Baronissi, Italy.
[src:university-of-salerno/university-of-salerno] Its main campus is located in Fisciano while the Faculty of Medicine is located in Baronissi.
[src:university-of-salerno/university-of-salerno] Another branch, the third overall, was opened in Avellino in 2023.
[src:university-of-salerno/university-of-salerno] It is organized into seventeen departments.
[src:university-of-salerno/university-of-salerno] Salerno's Schola Medica Salernitana was the most important medical school in Europe between the 10th and 13th centuries.
[src:university-of-salerno/university-of-salerno] Following the rise of university medical schools, it briefly merged with the University of Naples, which moved to Salerno from 1253 to 1258 before returning to Naples and establishing its own medical school there.
[src:university-of-salerno/university-of-salerno] Meanwhile, the University of Montpellier displaced Salerno as the most prestigious medical school internationally and by the 14th century the latter had ceased to exist.
[src:university-of-salerno/university-of-salerno] The modern University of Salerno traces its origin to the Istituto Universitario di Magistero "Giovanni Cuomo", a teacher training college founded in 1944 with this renowned and ancient tradition in mind.
[src:university-of-salerno/university-of-salerno] In 1968 the institute became a State university, the University of Salerno, and it has since seen a great increase in student numbers.
[src:university-of-salerno/university-of-salerno] Caianiello" (in Italian "Biblioteca umanistica "E.
[src:university-of-salerno/university-of-salerno] Caianiello") offers students over 800,000 bibliographic units and over 6,383 periodicals in its shelves.
[src:university-of-salerno/university-of-salerno] In May 2015 the University of Salerno saw the establishment of a new research institute, the International Centre for Studies and Research "Mediterranean Knowledge", composed by 14 Research Units located in universities of the Mediterranean countries.
[src:university-of-salerno/university-of-salerno] The ICSR, that has its administrative office at the University of Salerno, aims at favouring research and dissemination of knowledge about the most important topics of the Mediterranean Basin.
[src:university-of-salerno/university-of-salerno] For that purpose it publishes the book series *Mediterranean, Knowledge, Culture, Heritage*, the*Journal of Mediterranean Knowledge* and a series of Working Papers.
[src:university-of-salerno/university-of-salerno] The ICSR, moreover, periodically organizes national and international conferences.
